    <cas:Sofa xmi:id="1" sofaNum="1" sofaID="_InitialView" mimeType="text" sofaString="The status of future imports is not the only driver of concern for extreme levels of acute food insecurity and malnutrition in Yemen. Additional factors include increased conflict, significantly reduced economic activity leading to low household income and purchasing power, and the ongoing diphtheria and cholera outbreaks. Even in the absence of additional disruptions, FEWS NET expects large areas of the country to remain in Crisis (IPC Phase 3!) as large-scale provision of food assistance to 6-8 million people each month prevents a deterioration to worse levels. However, large populations within these areas will continue to face Emergency (IPC Phase 4) outcomes as emergency food assistance likely covers less than half of those in need. Food security for some populations may deteriorate to Catastrophe (IPC Phase 5) as they begin to face an extreme lack of food and other basic needs."/>
    <cas:View sofa="1" members="8 19 24 29 34 39 44 49 62 75 88 101 114 127 140 153 166 179 192 205 218 231 244 257 270 283 296 309 322 335 348 361 374 387 400 413 426 439 452 465 478 491 504 517 530 543 556 569 582 595 608 621 634 647 660 673 686 699 712 725 738 751 764 777 790 803 816 829 842 855 868 881 894 907 920 933 946 959 972 985 998 1011 1024 1037 1050 1063 1076 1089 1102 1115 1128 1141 1154 1167 1180 1193 1206 1219 1232 1245 1258 1271 1284 1297 1310 1323 1336 1349 1362 1375 1388 1401 1414 1427 1440 1453 1466 1479 1492 1505 1518 1531 1544 1557 1570 1583 1596 1609 1622 1635 1648 1661 1674 1687 1700 1713 1726 1739 1752 1765 1778 1791 1804 1817 1830 1843 1856 1869 1882 1895 1908 1921 1934 1947 1960 1973 1986 1999 2012 2025 2038 2051 2064 2077 2090 2103 2136 2126 2116 2121 2131 2162 2169 2176 2141 2148 2155 2190 2183 2193 2186 2197 2210"/>
